bases this prediction upon a matching of satellite transponder' b'demand and supply, particularly as new data compression techniques' b'appear to could double or triple transponder capacity using existing' b'or near-term transponders.' b'one of the significant possible changes in the market was' b'identified as the arrival of new launch vehicles, including russian' b'launch systems. but arianespace predicts that in the long term,' b'investors purchasing launch services are looking for the best trade' b'off between launch service quality and price, and that russian and' b'other new launch services will have to prove out their capabilities' b'and service quality, and their market penetration will be minimal.' b'[commentary: ariane releases their market surveys annually, and' b'i reported on their prior market survey in a past issue of csn/sti.' b"comparing the two surveys, there aren't outstanding differences in" b'the numbers. the most notable change is the consideration of new' b'data compression techniques, reducing the demand for new physical' b'transponders on orbit.' b'i note that in contrast to some predictions, demand for space-' b'based communications transponders appears to be remain strong. while' b'fiber optic lines are making substantial inroads into the' b'established point-to-point telecommunications markets, growing' b'demand for telecommunications services world wide and for point-to-' b'multipoint broadcast services have prevented a decrease in space' b'transponder demand. fiberoptic cables provide a higher capability' b'service, but only from established point a to established point b.' b'to establish a fiberoptic link it is necessary to install cable' b'between the points, and while there are improved network solutions,' b'installing a large network of distributed fiberoptic links can cost' b'millions or billions of dollars.' b'for broadcast services where there is not an existing ground' b'network structure, satellites still offer the most cost effective' b'solution. and if new services are required into a new region, it is' b'cheaper to install a small satellite link costing only a few tens of' b'thousands of dollars and tie into the existing global satellite' b'network. this allows rapid growth of new satellite services, and' b'has kept demand high. the replacement market for fiberoptics is' b'growing as well, since as demand grows between the points serviced,' b'it becomes cost effective to later install a fiberoptic link to' b'handle the increase in traffic.' b'since the telecommunications and data transfer markets are still' b'growing rapidly, satellite market projections remain rosy. but' b'satellites are also getting longer orbital lifetimes. current' b'generation satellites are now getting guarantees of at years of' b'on-orbit service or more, in contrast to years of service from' b"last generation's satellites. this has cut back some of the launch" b'demand, as satellite owners are rescheduling replacement satellite' b'launches over longer intervals.' b"and as last note; arianespace didn't flag it this year, but it" b'looks like the space transportation market will be rather over-' b'supplied by existing launch systems in the near term. the annual' b'commercial launch demand is for about medium sized satellites' b'per year. from the supply side, ariane is capable of launching up' b'to about a dozen medium sized satellites a year, delta is capable of' b'about per year, atlas is capable of long march b"japan's h-vehicle russia's proton capable of and other" b'systems such as zenit and soyuz another medium launches per' b"year. that's a lot of capability for a small market." b'we can only expect the competition to intensify for commercial' b'launches.]' b'' b'6- ntsb investigates pegasus launch over aborted abort' b'the feb pegasus launch by orbital sciences corporation has' b'spawned an investigation over an apparent violation of range safety' b'rules. a valid abort order from a nasa range safety officer to halt' b'the mission was overridden and the pegasus was launched in violation' b'of range safety rules.' b'in the last few minutes of the pegasus launch countdown, one of' b'two abort command receivers aboard the pegasus failed. such a failure' b'typically scrubs a launch,and a nasa range safety officer at' b'wallops island, va issued a mission abort order about a minute' b'before the scheduled pegasus launch. somehow this command was' b'overridden by the osc launch team or the message was lost in the' b'communications channels, and the pegasus was launched despite the' b'valid abort call.' b'fortunately, the pegasus functioned as expected, and the abort' b'command receiver was not needed. but this incident did spark an' b'investigation since a valid abort order was given under agreed-to' b'launch constraint rules, and was not obeyed.' b'leading the investigation is the national transportation safety' b'board (ntsb) with support from nasa, osc, and the air force. this' b'investigation marks the first time ntsb has taken the lead on an' b'incident involving a space launch. according to the ntsb, their' b'investigation will take about months, and is primarily looking at' b'lines of authority, communications links and safety procedures used' b'in the launch.' b'[commentary: this is the first time that the ntsb has led an' b'investigation into a space launch. their leadership was requested' b"by the department of commerce's office of commercial space" b'transportation, who had licensed the commercial launch.' b'at the time of writing this column, some of the initial' b'investigations have been concluded, and some of the results are' b'starting to leak out into the trade press. apparently, or four' b'different communications channels were in use during the test. after' b'the abort destruct receiver stopped responding, the nasa test' b'director and range controller in the mission control room at wallops' b'island gave abort orders about a minute before the launch.' b'according to the mission rules, this should have stopped the launch.' b'somehow, the osc test conductor ordered the abort reversed, and the' b'nasa communicator on the net relayed that order to the b-52 carrying' b'the pegasus at about seconds before launch. differing' b'explainations of exactly how this happened are proposed with the' b'best set being that clear lines of communications and clear' b'definition of the responsibilities of the mission control team, and' b'understanding of the mission rules were not established before the' b'launch.' b'as we see more and more commercial launches, more of these' b'procedural issues are going to crop up and will have to be resolved.' b'this case is interesting because it is the first time the ntsb has' b'been called in to investigate a commercial launch problem (as they' b'do with commercial aircraft problems).' b'i think this problem will turn out to be primarily problems with' b'procedures and communications, and will be cleared up with issuance' b'of guidelines on how launch communications should be set up and how' b'specific lines of authority should be delineated.]' b'' b'7- another pegasus competitor is announced' b'tsniimach enterprise in russia announced it is marketing a new' b'small space launch system, based upon converted icbm components.' b'two versions of the launcher are being marketed: the "aerokosmos"' b'winged vehicle launched like the osc pegasus, and the "severkosmos",' b'launched from a mobile ground transporter. the aerokosmos is' b'projected to deliver kg to a km circular orbit or kg to' b'an km circular orbit, and the severkosmos to be capable of b'kg to km orbits and kg to km. also proposed to be used' b'with these launch systems is a leo data relay system called' b"'sineva'. tsniimach enterprise is described as a ex-military" b'establishment, focusing on aerodynamics and thermal protection of' b'spacecraft and which has participated in the development of the' b'buran shuttle system, they are lo