' b'- can financing be found at low enough cost to support the' b'investment?' b'other commercial launch site ventures including those at' b'woomera, poker flat, cape york, white sands, alabama off-shore' b'platform, hawaii, and vandenberg have to also be judged against' b'these criteria. in my opinion, some of these ventures are flying' b'on hope and speculation, and not on sound financial grounds.]' b'' b"9- spain's capricornia launcher still proceeding" b'in one of his last official acts, former president bush' b'authorized space technology transfer for several joint space' b'ventures between us and other firms. one of these was a proposed' b'use of us technology by spain to build a small booster. with that' b'regulatory impediment removed, the 3-stage capricornia launch' b'vehicle will start development later this year, planning for a first' b'launch in the time period. the capricornia is described as' b'a small 3-stage all solid booster designed to put kg into' b'leo. several launch sites are being examined for the system,' b'including on the iberian peninsula and on the canary islands.' b'originated by inta in spain, the project reports it has m in' b"development funding, and will use technology from argentina's condor" b'launch vehicle as well as from the us.' b'[commentary: several firms have identified a market opportunity' b'in providing a small launcher for the european market. small' b'payloads from european firms or organizations currently use either' b'ariane piggyback launches or the us/italian scout launcher.' b'however, ariane piggyback opportunities are limited, and the scout' b'program is being phased out (accompanied by some disarray in the' b'italian government and space industry regarding any follow-on' b'system).' b'this has left an apparent niche for a new european small launch' b'system. surprisingly enough, esa has not supported development of' b'such a system within the current space funding structure. studies' b'have been performed by bri