nter/ swedish' b'space corp. program to upgrade the andoya rocket range in norway and' b'offering small satellite launches into the polar regions. according' b'to pacastro, pss is also performing an m upgrade of the andoya' b'launch facilities, including a new integration facility and a fully-' b'enclosed vertical assembly building for small launch vehicles like' b'the pacastro pa-2. pacastro has been chosen as "the main' b'alternative rocket supplier" for the small satellite launch service' b'to be offered by pss from andoya. the date of the launch of the' b'swedish satellite was not specified.' b'[commentary: pacastro has been trying to line up customers and' b'funding for their launch vehicle for some time now. the pa-2 is a' b'small, two stage rocket fueled by rp-1 and liquid oxygen. from' b"pacastro's literature, the engines designed for the pa-series" b'rockets are built of "off the shelf" components based upon the lunar' b'module descent engines built by trw, and are capable of putting a' b'225 kg satellite into a km circular polar orbit.' b'pacastro is trying to arrange construction financing for its' b'first three pa-2 vehicles, with a first launch planned for and' b'2 orbital launches planned for my records show pacastro hired' b'trw to provide marketing support and systems design, with primary' b'engineering to be done by aeroastro, a small satellite builder' b'closely associated with pacastro (headquartered in the same' b'building). the swedish space corporation would supply engineering,' b'launch operations, vehicle subsystems, and marketing support.' b'sumitomo corp. of tokyo, is a first round investor and sits on the' b'board of directors.' b'pacastro has gotten a first round financial package of at least' b'$550 k (some sources place this of high as m), but has been' b'searching for about a year for the additional m needed to' b'design, build and launch their first set of vehicles.' b'the launch reservation from ssc can possibly be used to help' b'bring some investors on board, but by my estimate, they will need' b'much more than the single m sale to put their venture into real' b'hardware.]' b'' b'11- china and taiwan joint satellite venture reported' b'in early march, it was reported a joint satellite communications' b'venture between a taiwanese and mainland chinese was in the works.' b'as reported in the taipei press, china development corp. (cdc),' b'headquartered in taiwam and with links to the ruling nationalist' b'party, is planning to set up a joint venture in hong kong with china' b'great wall industry corp. with the objective of launching a regional' b'communications satellite. cdc would cover about of the satellite' b'system cost (us m) in exchange for rights to of the' b"satellite's communications channels." b'[commentary: this announcement came close on the heels of the' b'release of taiwanese plans for space development (released in mid' b'january). in those plans, the national space program office of' b'taiwan will launch satellites, starting with rocsat-1, a kg' b'scientific spacecraft, planned for launch in two additional' b'satellites are planned, both communications satellites. trw has' b'been helping taiwan plan this program, budgeted at t$13.6 b (us b'm) through b"i haven't been able to establish any relationship between this" b'venture and those of the nspot, but there might be a connection.' b'while taiwan has the financing to pursue several ventures, the' b'current taiwanese telecommunications market might not support two' b'separate sastellite ventures.' b'the reported name for the tiawanese/chinese system is "asiasat-' b'2", but i don\'t thinks this has any relationship with the existing' b'hong kong-based "asiasat" program involving chinese, hong kong, and' b'other asian investors, other than using it as an organizational' b'model. there are some obvious advantages to pursuing such a joing' b'venture it could provide excellent first-hand experience to' b'taiwan for a very low cost, which then can be used in later' b'satellite ventures. but there are internal political issues between' b'taiwanese and chinese ventures, but putting any joint venture' b'through a hong kong intermediary corporation might allow it to' b'proceed.' b'in any case, the east asian satellite market is lighting up with' b'substantially growth projected in space services and revenues. this' b'is just another indicator to add to the list.]' b'' b'12- south korea announces national move into space technologies' b"south korea's trade, industry and resources ministry recently" b'announced plans to invest us$22 b in research and development and' b'another us$17 b into manufacturing and research facilities for' b'advanced aerospace technologies. space technologies have been' b'specifically targeted as part of this program, beginning with' b'manufacture and launch of an advanced multi-purpose satellite by' b"1997. the objective of this investment is to raise south korea's" b"aerospace technology to the level of the world's top countries by" b'2000.' b'[commentary: south korea has been quietly working to develop its' b'national aerospace industry, specifically including space' b"activities. i'm noting this as a flag that potential new players are" b'coming into the commercial space market.' b'as part of their national effort, national telecommunications' b'satellites for korea telecom will be launched in april and oct b'on delta. designated koreasat and the platforms will provide' b'television and telephone service throughout the korean peninsula,' b'southwestern japan and portions of china bordering north korea.' b'south korea launched its first small satellite piggyback on' b'ariane in aug called uribyol-1 (our star) and costing about us' b'$8.8 m. uribyol-2 is planned for piggyback launch in october of' b'this year, again on ariane, and will be entirely "made in korea."' b'uribyol-3, projected for a launch, will be an environment-' b'monitoring micro-satellite.' b'this satellite may be the precursor to a series of small earth' b'observation satellites, the keos (korean earth observation system)' b'project, which has been submitted for approval to the south korean' b'government, would use two or three 300-kg spacecraft equipped with' b'optical and microwave sensors.' b'south korean press reports claim there is also a parallel' b'military effort to establish the capabilities for building and' b'launching small military satellites by supposedly a' b'government panel had been established to oversee such an effort,' b'funded at us m between and in anticipation of an' b'expected pullout of u.s. intelligence-gathering systems from the' b'korean peninsula.' b'in conjunction with all of these reported efforts, south korean' b'is also pursuing production work either as off-sets to existing' b'aerospace technology contracts (for example, mcdonnell douglas is' b'offsetting production of some delta parts to south korean firms as' b'part of the koreasat launch contracts), or for production of' b'consumer space items (among other products, south korea exports' b'satellite receiver television setups to japan, and samsung has' b"announced teaming for production of osc's orbcomm user terminals.)." b'this looks like a very aggressive push into space technologies.' b'considering that east asia is currently the fastest growing sector' b'for commercial space services (primarily for telecommunications), a' b'south korean push into space technologies may change the composition' b'of commercial space market there over the next decade.]' b'' b'13- space technology indexes through march' b'as announced in the last csn/sti, each issue will give the' b'results of stock indexes and portfolios regarding space stocks and' b'investments. the table below summarizes results to the end of' b'march. the space technology index did quite a bit better than the' b'market as a whole, as represented by the s&p index. since b'of the values included in the index are us firms, this rep